\f1\b\fs32 \cf0 . Rules Engine\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs26 \cf0 The Event is:\
\'93Something happened.\'94\
The Rule decides:\
\'93What does this mean?\'94\
Example:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf0 EVENT:\
PEP status changed\
\
RULE:\
If customer becomes PEP\
\
THEN:\
- Increase risk\
- Require EDD\
- Create compliance task\
- Notify responsible consultant\
- Set review deadline\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26 \cf0 Technically:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf0 class ComplianceRule:\
    event_type = "PEP_STATUS_CHANGED"\
\
    def evaluate(self, event):\
        return \{\
            "create_task": True,\
            "create_case": True,\
            "notify": True,\
            "risk_impact": 30\
        \}\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26 \cf0 However, I make the rules 
\f1\b data-driven
\f0\b0  rather than hardcoded.\
For example:\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\fs24 \cf0 RULE: PEP detected\
IF:\
    event.type = PEP_STATUS_CHANGED\
    AND new_status = true\
\
THEN:\
    risk_score += 30\
    create_task = "Perform EDD"\
    notification = "HIGH"\
    deadline = 5 days\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26 \cf0 This allows a compliance administrator to configure rules without changing the code.\
\uc0\u8232 \
\uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

